Claims CLAIMS:  What is claimed is: 1. A process for reducing fouling in a refrigeration system, comprising: compressing a refrigerant to produce a compressed refrigerant, wherein the refrigerant comprises ethane, ethylene, propane, propylene, or a mixture thereof; condensing at least a portion of the compressed refrigerant to produce a first liquid phase refrigerant at a first pressure; reducing a pressure of the first liquid phase refrigerant to produce a second liquid phase refrigerant at a second pressure; separating at least a portion of any vapor phase refrigerant from the second liquid phase refrigerant to produce a first exchanger duty liquid phase refrigerant; combining a liquid solvent with the first exchanger duty liquid phase refrigerant to produce a solvent modified liquid phase refrigerant, wherein the solvent is selected from the group consisting of: a first mixture comprising methanol and ethanol, a second mixture comprising methanol and n-propanol, a third mixture comprising ethanol and n-propanol, a C 5 -C 7 paraffinic hydrocarbon, and a fourth mixture comprising at least two C 5 -C 7 paraffinic hydrocarbons; and indirectly exchanging heat from a process fluid to the solvent modified liquid phase refrigerant and dissolving at least a portion of a contaminant in the solvent to produce a cooled process fluid and a heated contaminant-rich solvent modified refrigerant, wherein the contaminant comprises a hydrocarbon oil. 2. The process of claim 1, further comprising: separating a vaporized refrigerant and a contaminant-rich solvent from the heated contaminant-rich solvent modified refrigerant; compressing the vaporized refrigerant to produce additional compressed refrigerant; condensing at least a portion of the additional compressed refrigerant to produce additional first liquid phase refrigerant at the first pressure; reducing a pressure of the additional first liquid phase refrigerant to produce additional second liquid phase refrigerant at the second pressure; 

 separating at least a portion of any vapor phase refrigerant from the additional second liquid phase refrigerant and combining the additional second liquid phase refrigerant with the contaminant-rich solvent to produce a second exchanger duty liquid phase refrigerant; and removing at least a portion of the solvent comprising the dissolved contaminant from the second exchanger duty liquid phase refrigerant to produce a contaminant-lean second exchanger duty liquid phase refrigerant. 3. The process of claim 2, indirectly exchanging heat from additional process fluid to the contaminant-lean second exchanger duty liquid phase refrigerant to produce a cooled additional process fluid and a heated contaminant-lean refrigerant. 4. The process of any one of claims 1 to 3, wherein the hydrocarbon oil comprises a seal oil, a lubrication oil, or a mixture thereof. 5. The process of any one of claims 1 to 4, wherein the hydrocarbon oil has an ISO viscosity classification of ISO VG 7 to ISO VG 150 as defined by ISO 3448: 1992. 6. The process of any one of claims 1 to 5, wherein the solvent modified liquid phase refrigerant comprises about 1 vol. % to about 25 vol. % of the solvent, based on a volume of the solvent modified liquid phase refrigerant. 7. The process of any one of claims 1 to 6, wherein the solvent comprises the C5-C7 paraffinic hydrocarbon. 8. The process of any one of claims 1 to 6, wherein the solvent comprises the fourth mixture comprising at least two C5-C7 paraffinic hydrocarbons. 9. The process of any one of claims 1 to 6, wherein the solvent comprises the fourth mixture comprising at least two C5-C7 paraffinic hydrocarbons, and wherein an amount of each of the at least two C5-C7 paraffinic hydrocarbons in the fourth mixture provides the solvent with a freezing point that is within 20Â°C of a eutectic freeze point of the fourth mixture. 10. The process of any one of claims 1 to 6, wherein the solvent comprises at least one Cs- Ci paraffinic hydrocarbon, and wherein the at least one C5-C7 paraffinic hydrocarbon has an atmospheric boiling point of about 55Â°C to about 95Â°C. 11. A process for reducing fouling in a refrigeration system, comprising: contacting an exchanger duty liquid phase refrigerant with a solvent to produce a solvent modified liquid phase refrigerant comprising about 1 vol. % to about 25 vol. % of the solvent, based on a volume of the solvent modified liquid phase refrigerant, wherein: the refrigerant comprises ethane, ethylene, propane, propylene, or a mixture thereof, and the solvent is selected from the group consisting of: a first mixture comprising methanol and ethanol, a second mixture comprising methanol and n-propanol, a third mixture comprising ethanol and n-propanol, a C 5 -C 7 paraffinic hydrocarbon, and a fourth mixture comprising two or more C5-C7 paraffinic hydrocarbons; flowing the solvent modified liquid phase refrigerant through an apparatus comprising a contaminant disposed on an inner surface thereof, wherein the solvent dissolves at least a portion of the contaminant as the solvent modified liquid phase refrigerant flows through the apparatus to produce a contaminant-rich solvent modified refrigerant, and wherein the contaminant comprises a hydrocarbon oil; and removing at least a portion of the solvent comprising the dissolved contaminant from the contaminant-rich solvent modified refrigerant to produce a contaminant-lean refrigerant. 12. The process of claim 11, wherein the hydrocarbon oil comprises a seal oil, a lubrication oil, or a mixture thereof. 13. The process of claim 11 or 12, wherein the hydrocarbon oil has an ISO viscosity classification of ISO VG 7 to ISO VG 150 as defined by ISO 3448:1992. 14. The process of any one of claims 11 to 13, wherein the solvent comprises n-hexane. 15. The process of any one of claims 11 to 14, wherein the solvent comprises an iso-hexane. 16. The process of any one of claims 11 to 13, wherein: the solvent modified refrigerant comprises the first mixture, and wherein the first mixture comprises about 20 vol. % to about 40 vol. % of methanol, based on a combined amount of methanol and ethanol at atmospheric pressure and a temperature of about 25Â°C, the solvent modified refrigerant comprises the second mixture, and wherein the second mixture comprises about 50 vol. % to about 70 vol. % of methanol, based on a combined amount of methanol and n-propanol at atmospheric pressure and a temperature of about 25Â°C, or the solvent modified refrigerant comprises the third mixture, and wherein the third mixture comprises about 50 vol. % to about 70 vol. % of ethanol, based on a combined amount of ethanol and n-propanol at atmospheric pressure and a temperature of about 25Â°C. 17. The process of any one of claims 11 to 16, wherein the refrigerant comprises ethane, ethylene, or a mixture thereof. 18. The process of any one of claims 11 to 17, wherein the refrigerant comprises propane, propylene, or a mixture thereof. 19. The process of any one of claims 11 to 13, wherein the solvent comprises n-hexane, an iso-hexane, or a mixture thereof, and wherein the refrigerant comprises ethylene. 20. A refrigeration system, comprising: a compression unit configured to compress a refrigerant to produce a compressed refrigerant, wherein the refrigerant comprises ethane, ethylene, propane, propylene, or a mixture thereof; a first heat exchanger configured to condense at least a portion of the compressed refrigerant to produce a first liquid phase refrigerant at a first pressure; an apparatus configured to reduce a pressure of the first liquid phase refrigerant to produce a second liquid phase refrigerant at a second pressure; a separator configured to remove at least a portion of any vapor phase refrigerant from the second liquid phase refrigerant to produce an exchanger duty liquid phase refrigerant, 

 a first conduit configured to introduce a solvent to the exchanger duty liquid phase refrigerant to produce a solvent modified liquid phase refrigerant, wherein the solvent is selected from the group consisting of: a first mixture comprising methanol and ethanol, a second mixture comprising methanol and n-propanol, a third mixture comprising ethanol and n-propanol, a C5-C7 paraffinic hydrocarbon, and a fourth mixture comprising C5-C7 paraffinic hydrocarbons; and a second heat exchanger configured to indirectly exchange heat from a process fluid to the solvent modified liquid phase refrigerant to produce a cooled process fluid and a heated solvent modified refrigerant. 21. The system of claim 20, wherein the separator is further configured to separate a vaporized refrigerant from the heated solvent modified refrigerant to produce a separated vaporized refrigerant and a contaminant-rich solvent. 22. The system of claim 20 or 21, wherein the refrigeration system is an open loop refrigeration system. 23. The system of claim 20 or 21, wherein the refrigeration system is a closed loop refrigeration system. 24. The system of any one of clams 20 to 23, wherein the compression unit comprises a multistage compressor. 25. A process for reducing fouling in a refrigeration system, comprising: compressing a refrigerant to produce a compressed refrigerant, wherein the refrigerant comprises ethane, ethylene, propane, propylene, or a mixture thereof; condensing at least a portion of the compressed refrigerant to produce a first liquid phase refrigerant at a first pressure; reducing a pressure of the first liquid phase refrigerant to produce a second liquid phase refrigerant at a second pressure; 

 separating at least a portion of any vapor phase refrigerant from the second liquid phase refrigerant to produce a first exchanger duty liquid phase refrigerant; combining a liquid solvent with the first exchanger duty liquid phase refrigerant to produce a solvent modified liquid phase refrigerant, wherein the solvent an iso-hexane, hexane, or a mixture thereof; indirectly exchanging heat from a process fluid to the solvent modified liquid phase refrigerant and dissolving at least a portion of a contaminant in the solvent to produce a first process fluid and a heated contaminant-rich solvent modified refrigerant, wherein the contaminant comprises a hydrocarbon oil having an ISO viscosity classification of ISO VG 7 to ISO VG 150 as defined by ISO 3448: 1992; separating a vaporized refrigerant and a contaminant-rich solvent from the heated contaminant-rich solvent modified refrigerant; and removing at least a portion of the contaminant-rich solvent comprising the dissolved contaminant from the process.
